        geekModeText: "Astragalus membranaceus extracts contain a complex mixture of bioactive compounds, including triterpenoid saponins (astragalosides), flavonoids, and polysaccharides. The most researched mechanism regarding aging is its potential to activate telomerase. Certain fractions of Astragalus have been shown to upregulate the expression of TERT (Telomerase Reverse Transcriptase), the catalytic subunit of the telomerase enzyme. This activity helps to maintain or elongate telomeres in proliferative cells, such as hematopoietic stem cells and T-lymphocytes, thereby delaying replicative senescence and preventing Stem Cell Exhaustion.<sup>31</sup>  \nBeyond telomeres, Astragalus polysaccharides (APS) exhibit potent immunomodulatory effects. They bind to TLR4 receptors on macrophages and dendritic cells, stimulating the release of cytokines and enhancing phagocytic activity. Astragalus also exerts anti-inflammatory effects by inhibiting the NF-κB pathway and reducing the expression of adhesion molecules (ICAM-1, VCAM-1) on endothelial cells. Furthermore, components like Astragaloside IV improve mitochondrial function by preserving the mitochondrial membrane potential and inhibiting the opening of the mitochondrial permeability transition pore (mPTP) under stress conditions.<sup>33</sup>",
        sources: [{ "id": "31", "text": "A Natural Astragalus-Based Nutritional Supplement Lengthens Telomeres in a Middle-Aged Population: A Randomized, Double-Blind, Placebo-Controlled Study \\- MDPI", "url": "https://www.mdpi.com/2072-6643/16/17/2963" }, { "id": "33", "text": "A Review of Astragalus Root Extract: Pharmacological Actions and Anti-Aging Mechanisms", "url": "https://www.herbalgram.org/resources/herbclip/issues/2025/issue-762/astragalus-root-extract/" }],
