        geekModeText: "Cycloastragenol is a triterpenoid aglycone derived from the hydrolysis of Astragaloside IV. It is identified as the primary small molecule within Astragalus responsible for telomerase activation. Cycloastragenol acts by transiently increasing the transcription of hTERT, leading to increased telomerase activity in somatic cells. This elongation of critically short telomeres rescues cells from the Hayflick limit, allowing for continued cell division and tissue regeneration. This is particularly relevant for the skin (keratinocytes) and the immune system (CD4/CD8 T-cells), where telomere attrition limits functional capacity.<sup>35</sup>  \nIn addition to Telomere Attrition, Cycloastragenol impacts the ERK1/2 signaling pathway, promoting cell proliferation and survival. It has been shown to improve lipid metabolism and wound healing in vivo. Recent studies suggest it also modulates the Nrf2/proteasome axis, enhancing the degradation of damaged proteins (Loss of Proteostasis) and upregulating antioxidant enzymes. By maintaining telomere length, Cycloastragenol indirectly prevents Genomic Instability, as critically short telomeres can lead to chromosome fusion and breakage-fusion-bridge cycles.<sup>37</sup>",
