        geekModeText: "Astragaloside IV (AS-IV) is the major saponin found in Astragalus root. While it serves as a precursor to cycloastragenol, AS-IV possesses distinct pharmacological properties. It acts as a potent anti-inflammatory agent by inhibiting the HMGB1/TLR4/NF-κB signaling axis, which is critical for suppressing the \"sterile inflammation\" associated with tissue damage and aging. AS-IV also protects endothelial cells from oxidative stress-induced dysfunction by activating the Nrf2/HO-1 pathway and increasing nitric oxide (NO) production via eNOS phosphorylation.<sup>39</sup>  \nIn the context of cardiovascular health, AS-IV inhibits cardiac hypertrophy and fibrosis by blocking the TGF-β1/Smad signaling pathway. It also improves mitochondrial bioenergetics by regulating calcium homeostasis; it inhibits the calcium overload induced by ischemia/reperfusion injury by modulating the Na+/K+ ATPase and SERCA pumps. This preservation of mitochondrial integrity prevents apoptosis and supports energy metabolism in high-demand tissues like the heart and brain. Furthermore, AS-IV promotes angiogenesis via the VEGF/KDR pathway, improving microcirculation in aged tissues.<sup>41</sup>",
