        geekModeText: "Gynostemma pentaphyllum, often called \"Southern Ginseng,\" contains a vast array of dammarane-type saponins known as gypenosides, some of which are identical to ginsenosides (e.g., Rb1, Rd). The primary geroprotective mechanism of Gynostemma is the potent, biphasic activation of AMP-activated protein kinase (AMPK). AMPK acts as the cellular energy sensor; its activation by gypenosides signals a low-energy state, triggering catabolic pathways like fatty acid oxidation and glucose uptake (via GLUT4 translocation) while inhibiting anabolic pathways like lipogenesis (via ACC inhibition).<sup>43</sup>  \nThis AMPK activation also stimulates mitochondrial biogenesis through the PGC-1α pathway and promotes autophagy via mTOR inhibition, directly addressing Deregulated Nutrient Sensing and Mitochondrial Dysfunction. Gypenosides have also been shown to activate SIRT1, linking metabolic regulation to epigenetic stability. Furthermore, Gynostemma exhibits \"adaptogenic\" properties by modulating the Nrf2 pathway to enhance endogenous antioxidant defenses (SOD, Catalase) during stress, while simultaneously suppressing NF-κB mediated inflammation. This dual action helps maintain homeostasis in the face of metabolic and environmental stressors.<sup>43</sup>",
        sources: [{ "id": "43", "text": "The effect of an orally‐dosed Gynostemma pentaphyllum extract (ActivAMP®) on body composition in overweight, adult men and women: A double‐blind, randomised, placebo‐controlled study \\- PMC \\- PubMed Central", "url": "https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9291581/" }],
