        geekModeText: "Polydatin is the natural glucoside precursor of resveratrol (resveratrol-3-O-β-mono-D-glucoside). The glucose moiety protects the stilbene structure from rapid oxidation and enzymatic degradation in the gut, potentially offering a different bioavailability profile than resveratrol. Polydatin enters cells via active glucose transport mechanisms (SGLT1) and can be hydrolyzed to resveratrol or act directly. It functions as a potent antioxidant, blocking the malondialdehyde (MDA) pathway and scavenging ROS to protect mitochondria from oxidative damage. It preserves mitochondrial membrane potential and inhibits the opening of the mPTP.<sup>61</sup>  \nPolydatin strongly activates the SIRT1/Nrf2 axis, enhancing cellular antioxidant defenses. It is particularly effective in lipid metabolism, where it regulates the expression of PPAR-α and SREBP-1c, promoting fatty acid oxidation and inhibiting lipogenesis. This modulation helps prevent hepatic steatosis and improves insulin sensitivity. Additionally, Polydatin has been shown to inhibit the NLRP3 inflammasome, a multiprotein complex that drives inflammation in response to danger signals, thereby reducing IL-1β and IL-18 secretion and addressing Chronic Inflammation.<sup>62</sup>",
