        geekModeText: "L-Theanine (N-ethyl-L-glutamine) is a non-protein amino acid found in tea leaves. It crosses the blood-brain barrier via the leucine-preferring transport system. Structurally similar to glutamate, it binds to glutamate receptors (AMPA, Kainate, NMDA) but acts as a competitive antagonist, preventing glutamate-induced excitotoxicity. Its most profound effect is the modulation of inhibitory neurotransmitters; it increases the levels of GABA, dopamine, and glycine in the brain. This shift in neurochemistry promotes the generation of alpha brain waves (8–12 Hz), inducing a state of \"relaxed alertness\" without sedation.<sup>64</sup>  \nL-Theanine also exerts neuroprotective effects by inhibiting the downregulation of GABA(A) receptors during stress. It acts as an antioxidant, mitigating oxidative damage in neuronal cells. Furthermore, it interacts with the glutamate transporter (GLT-1), preventing the accumulation of extracellular glutamate. Studies suggest it can ameliorate sleep quality by reducing sympathetic nervous system activation and lowering cortisol levels. By optimizing neurotransmitter balance, it improves Altered Intercellular Communication in neural circuits.<sup>66</sup>",
