        geekModeText: "Silymarin is a complex of flavonolignans (silybin, silychristin, silydianin) derived from Silybum marianum. Silybin is the most biologically active component. Its primary mechanism is hepatoprotection via membrane stabilization; it prevents the uptake of toxins (like phalloidin or amanitin) by blocking specific transport proteins (OATPs) on the hepatocyte membrane. Intracellularly, silymarin stimulates RNA Polymerase I activity, increasing ribosomal RNA (rRNA) synthesis. This boosts the ribosome pool and enhances protein synthesis, accelerating the regeneration of damaged liver tissue (reversing Loss of Proteostasis).<sup>68</sup>  \nSilymarin acts as a potent antioxidant, scavenging free radicals and increasing intracellular Glutathione (GSH) and Superoxide Dismutase (SOD) levels. It inhibits the NF-κB pathway and the 5-LOX enzyme, reducing hepatic inflammation. Furthermore, it exerts anti-fibrotic effects by blocking the TGF-β1 signaling pathway, which prevents the transformation of hepatic stellate cells into myofibroblasts. This multi-targeted approach preserves liver function, which is central to systemic detoxification and metabolic regulation in aging.<sup>70</sup>",
