        geekModeText: "Rhodiola Rosea is a classic adaptogen, with its effects mediated primarily by phenylpropanoids (rosavins) and phenylethanoids (salidroside). Its hallmark mechanism is the modulation of the HPA axis; it inhibits the excessive release of Corticotropin-Releasing Factor (CRF) and lowers cortisol levels during chronic stress, preventing \"adrenal burnout.\" At the cellular level, Salidroside activates the AMPK pathway, stimulating glucose uptake and fatty acid oxidation in muscle cells, similar to exercise. It also upregulates the expression of Heat Shock Proteins (HSP70), which act as molecular chaperones to prevent protein aggregation (Loss of Proteostasis).<sup>88</sup>  \nRhodiola acts as a mild mitochondrial uncoupler, improving the efficiency of oxidative phosphorylation while reducing superoxide generation. It inhibits Monoamine Oxidases A and B (MAO-A/B), increasing the synaptic availability of serotonin, dopamine, and norepinephrine in the brain. This leads to improved mood, focus, and cognitive function under fatigue. Additionally, Rhodiola stimulates the expression of SIRT1 and activates the FOXO defense pathway, promoting stress resistance and longevity in model organisms.<sup>90</sup>",
        sources: [{ "id": "88", "text": "Rhodiola Rosea Extract Counteracts Stress in an Adaptogenic Response Curve Manner via Elimination of ROS and Induction of Neurite Outgrowth \\- PubMed Central", "url": "https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9122715/" }, { "id": "90", "text": "Rhodiola rosea L.: an herb with anti-stress, anti-aging, and immunostimulating properties for cancer chemoprevention \\- NIH", "url": "https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6208354/" }],
