        synergyDetails: { "partner": "Zinc", "mechanism": "Spermidine synthesis and function can be influenced by zinc availability; both are critical for cellular growth and differentiation.", "impact": "Supports cellular renewal and Cognition." },
        geekModeText: "Spermidine is a natural polyamine that is a critical caloric restriction mimetic. Its primary mechanism is the induction of autophagy via the inhibition of the acetyltransferase EP300. EP300 normally inhibits autophagy by acetylating key autophagy proteins (like ATG5, ATG7, LC3). Spermidine suppresses EP300, keeping these proteins in a deacetylated, active state. It also activates AMPK and inhibits mTORC1, reinforcing the autophagic flux. This clearance of cellular debris is vital for cardiac and neuronal health.<sup>100</sup>  \nA unique and crucial mechanism of spermidine is the hypusination of the translation factor eIF5A. Spermidine provides the aminobutyl group for the post-translational modification of eIF5A. Hypusinated eIF5A is essential for the translation of proteins containing polyproline motifs, which includes many proteins involved in autophagy (like TFEB) and mitochondrial respiration. By maintaining eIF5A hypusination, spermidine preserves mitochondrial function and protein synthesis fidelity in aging B-cells and neurons, reversing immunosenescence and cognitive decline.<sup>102</sup>",
        sources: [{ "id": "100", "text": "Molecular basis of the 'anti-aging' effect of spermidine and other natural polyamines \\- a mini-review \\- PubMed", "url": "https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24481223/" }, { "id": "102", "text": "Full article: The curious case of polyamines: spermidine drives reversal of B cell senescence", "url": "https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/15548627.2019.1698210" }],
