        geekModeText: "Lion's Mane mushroom contains two distinct classes of neurotrophic compounds: Hericenones (found in the fruiting body) and Erinacines (found in the mycelium). These small molecules (diterpenoids) can cross the blood-brain barrier. They stimulate the synthesis of Nerve Growth Factor (NGF) and Brain-Derived Neurotrophic Factor (BDNF) in astrocytes and neurons. NGF/BDNF binding to TrkA/TrkB receptors activates the PI3K/Akt and MAPK/ERK pathways, which promotes neurite outgrowth, branching, and synaptogenesis.<sup>103</sup>  \nThis neurotrophic support is critical for maintaining synaptic density and plasticity (Altered Intercellular Communication) and protecting neurons from apoptosis. Lion's Mane also reduces neuroinflammation by inhibiting the production of TNF-α and IL-6 in microglia. In models of Alzheimer's disease, it has been shown to reduce amyloid-beta plaque burden and prevent cognitive impairment, potentially by enhancing the degradation of Aβ via increased expression of insulin-degrading enzyme (IDE).<sup>105</sup>",
        sources: [{ "id": "103", "text": "Neurohealth Properties of Hericium erinaceus Mycelia Enriched with Erinacines \\- PMC", "url": "https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5987239/" }, { "id": "105", "text": "Hericerin derivatives from Hericium erinaceus exert BDNF-like neurotrophic activity in central hippocampal neurons and enhance memory | bioRxiv", "url": "https://www.biorxiv.org/content/10.1101/2020.08.28.271676.full" }],
