        geekModeText: "Holy Basil (Ocimum tenuiflorum) functions as an adaptogen primarily through its active compounds like eugenol, ursolic acid, and rosmarinic acid. Its key mechanism is the modulation of the Hypothalamic-Pituitary-Adrenal (HPA) axis, reducing the secretion of cortisol during stress. It inhibits the enzyme 11β-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase type 1 (11β-HSD1), which converts inactive cortisone to active cortisol, thereby lowering intracellular cortisol levels. This protects neurons and other tissues from the deleterious effects of chronic glucocorticoid exposure.<sup>111</sup>  \nHoly Basil also exhibits potent anti-inflammatory effects by inhibiting the COX-2 and LOX-5 enzymes. It improves Deregulated Nutrient Sensing by enhancing insulin secretion and sensitivity, possibly via PPAR-gamma activation. In the CNS, it modulates neurotransmitters, antagonizing the stress-induced changes in serotonin and dopamine levels. Additionally, it boosts endogenous antioxidant defenses (SOD, Catalase) via Nrf2 activation, protecting against heavy metal toxicity and radiation injury.<sup>113</sup>",
        sources: [{ "id": "111", "text": "Tulsi (Holy basil): Ancient Herb, Modern Medicine? Exploring Health Benefits and Research, -Ancient-herb-modern-medicine-Exploring-the-health-benefits-and-research.aspx)", "url": "https://www.news-medical.net/health/Tulsi-(Holy-basil)-Ancient-herb-modern-medicine-Exploring-the-health-benefits-and-research.aspx" }, { "id": "113", "text": "A randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled trial investigating the effects of an Ocimum tenuiflorum (Holy Basil) extract (HolixerTM) on stress, mood, and sleep in adults experiencing stress \\- PubMed Central", "url": "https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9524226/" }],
