        synergyDetails: { "partner": "Zinc", "mechanism": "Zinc modulates NMDA receptors; Magnolia modulates GABA.", "impact": "Balanced inhibition/excitation, enhancing Calm and Sleep." },
        geekModeText: "Magnolia bark is a source of two neolignans: Honokiol and Magnolol. These compounds are positive allosteric modulators of the GABAA receptor, enhancing chloride influx and promoting neuronal inhibition (anxiolysis/sedation) without the side effects of benzodiazepines. Magnolol also acts as a partial agonist at Cannabinoid Receptor 2 (CB2), which contributes to its anti-inflammatory and analgesic properties. Both compounds inhibit the NF-κB and STAT3 pathways, suppressing neuroinflammation and cytokine release.<sup>115</sup>  \nHonokiol, specifically, activates SIRT3 in the mitochondria. SIRT3 deacetylation of mitochondrial enzymes (like SOD2) enhances oxidative stress resistance and metabolic flexibility. This mitochondrial protection is vital for preventing neuronal death (Loss of Proteostasis). Furthermore, Magnolia extracts reduce corticosterone levels, dampening the stress response. They act as \"senomorphics\" by inhibiting the SASP, thus reducing the systemic inflammatory burden of aging.<sup>117</sup>",
        sources: [{ "id": "115", "text": "What is Magnolia Bark Good For? \\- Sentia Spirits", "url": "https://sentiaspirits.com/blogs/sentia-club-blog/sentia-ingredient-spotlight-magnolia" }, { "id": "117", "text": "Neuro-Modulating Effects of Honokiol: A Review \\- PMC \\- PubMed Central", "url": "https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3769637/" }],
