        geekModeText: "Trehalose is a disaccharide that functions as a chemical chaperone and an mTOR-independent autophagy inducer. As a chaperone, it directly stabilizes protein structures, preventing the aggregation of misfolded proteins (like huntingtin, tau, and alpha-synuclein) by replacing water molecules and forming a protective \"glass-like\" matrix around the protein. This preserves native conformation under stress conditions (Loss of Proteostasis).<sup>123</sup>  \nMechanistically, trehalose induces autophagy by inhibiting the SLC2A (GLUT) glucose transporters. This inhibition creates a state of pseudo-starvation that activates AMPK and phosphorylates ULK1, initiating autophagy without suppressing mTORC1 directly. It also promotes the nuclear translocation of TFEB (Transcription Factor EB), the master regulator of lysosomal biogenesis and autophagy genes. This enhances the lysosomal capacity to degrade cellular debris. Trehalose's ability to clear aggregates makes it a promising candidate for neurodegenerative diseases.<sup>125</sup>",
