        geekModeText: "Alpha-Ketoglutarate (AKG) is a key intermediate in the Krebs cycle. Ca-AKG acts as an obligate cofactor for Ten-Eleven Translocation (TET) enzymes (DNA demethylation) and Jumonji C-domain containing histone demethylases (JHDMs). By fueling these enzymes, AKG maintains the \"epigenetic landscape,\" preventing the hypermethylation drift characteristic of aging (Epigenetic Alterations). Supplementation has been shown to reverse biological age as measured by DNA methylation clocks.<sup>151</sup>  \nAKG also inhibits the ATP synthase subunit (specifically the alpha subunit), which lowers ATP levels slightly and inhibits the mTOR pathway, mimicking caloric restriction. This induces autophagy and extends lifespan in *C. elegans* and mice. Furthermore, AKG bridges cellular energy metabolism with amino acid homeostasis (glutamate/glutamine conversion) and detoxifies ammonia. In humans, Ca-AKG reduces inflammatory cytokines (IL-10, IL-6) and improves frailty scores, compressing morbidity.<sup>153</sup>",
