        geekModeText: "Beta-Hydroxybutyrate (BHB) is a ketone body that serves as an efficient alternative fuel for the brain and heart, bypassing glucose metabolism defects (insulin resistance). However, its signaling role is paramount. BHB acts as an endogenous inhibitor of Class I Histone Deacetylases (HDACs). This inhibition increases histone acetylation (e.g., at the FOXO3a promoter), activating genes involved in oxidative stress resistance and longevity. This epigenetic modification protects cells from oxidative damage.<sup>155</sup>  \nBHB also binds to the HCAR2 receptor (GPR109A) on immune cells, blocking the assembly of the NLRP3 inflammasome. This prevents the processing and release of IL-1β and IL-18, significantly dampening sterile inflammation and neuroinflammation. Metabolically, BHB oxidation increases the ratio of acetyl-CoA/succinyl-CoA and alters the NAD+/NADH ratio, influencing mitochondrial thermodynamics and reducing ROS generation. It is a key mediator of the benefits of fasting and ketogenic diets.<sup>157</sup>",
