        geekModeText: "Glutathione (GSH) is the most abundant endogenous antioxidant, a tripeptide (Glu-Cys-Gly). Its sulfhydryl group acts as a reducing equivalent for Glutathione Peroxidase (GPx) enzymes, which detoxify hydrogen peroxide and lipid peroxides. GSH is critical for maintaining the intracellular redox state; a decline in the GSH/GSSG ratio triggers apoptosis. GSH also forms conjugates with xenobiotics via Glutathione S-Transferases (GSTs), facilitating their excretion (Phase II detoxification).<sup>168</sup>  \nDirect oral supplementation of GSH faces challenges with bioavailability due to intestinal peptidase breakdown. However, liposomal forms or sublingual delivery can bypass this. Intracellularly, GSH protects telomeres from oxidative attrition and prevents protein oxidation (glutathionylation). It is essential for T-cell proliferation and function (Immunity). Mitochondrial GSH is distinct from the cytosolic pool and is vital for preventing mPTP opening and cell death.<sup>170</sup>",
